Three-state boolean value which includes 'default' setting which should be interpreted the same as a missing boolean value, to simulate the optionality of a wrapped primitive boolean parameter. The default value is used by various configuration implementations to set the config value when none is specified.

Validation rules used for ValueObject and XML output and Method Parameters. See http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#rf-facets for XML constraints.

The restriction base type for the XML schema. Defaults to simpleType datatype, but can refer to a defined type with specific restrictions (must include the namespace for non xs datatypes). For attributes/parameters. the incoming type (String) is cast to the restriction type (i.e. Integer, Date) for validation purposes. Must be a valid XML primitive datatype (automatically converted to Java datatype). Can be used to make the XML datatype more restrictive.
length and totalDigits is fixed: Must be exactly the length specified. String only.
length is the number of units of length. for string, length is measured in units of characters. Must be a non-negative integer,>= minLength and <= maxLength. String only.
Constraining a ·value space· to values with at least a specific number of units of length. String only.
Constraining a ·value space· to values with no more than a specific number of units of length. Must be <= length. String only.

a constraint on the ·value space· of a datatype which is achieved by constraining the ·lexical space· to literals which match a specific pattern. The value of pattern ·must· be a ·regular expression·. Example ZipCode=[0-9]{5}(-[0-9]{4})? String only.
constrains the ·value space· of types ·derived· from string. whiteSpace must be one of {preserve, replace, collapse}. String only.

Inclusive upper bound· of the ·value space· for a datatype with the ·ordered· property. The value of maxInclusive ·must· be in the ·value space· of the base type, i.e. limits values to integers less than or equal to 100. If the ·numeric· property is true, then the value ·must· be numerically less than or equal to {value}; if the ·numeric· property in {fundamental facets} is false (i.e., {base type definition} is one of the date and time related datatypes), then the value ·must· be chronologically less than or equal to {value}; Numeric and Date only.

Exclusive upper bound· of the ·value space· for a datatype with the ·ordered· property. The value of maxExclusive ·must· be in the ·value space· of the base type, i.e. limits values to integers less than or equal to 100. If the ·numeric· property is true, then the value ·must· be numerically less than or equal to {value}; if the ·numeric· property in {fundamental facets} is false (i.e., {base type definition} is one of the date and time related datatypes), then the value ·must· be chronologically less than or equal to {value}; Numeric and Date only.

Exclusive lower bound· of the ·value space· for a datatype with the ·ordered· property. The value of minExclusive ·must· be in the ·value space· of the ·base type· or be equal to {value} in {base type definition}, i.e. limits values to integers greater than or equal to 100. If the ·numeric· property is true, then the value ·must· be numerically greater than or equal to {value}; if the ·numeric· property in {fundamental facets} is false (i.e., {base type definition} is one of the date and time related datatypes), then the value ·must· be chronologically greater than or equal to {value}; Numeric and Date only.

Inclusive lower bound of the ·value space· for a datatype with the ·ordered· property. The value of minInclusive ·must· be in the ·value space· of the ·base type·, i.e. limits values to integers greater than or equal to 100. If the ·numeric· property is true, then the value ·must· be numerically greater than or equal to {value}; if the ·numeric· property in {fundamental facets} is false (i.e., {base type definition} is one of the date and time related datatypes), then the value ·must· be chronologically greater than or equal to {value}; Numeric and Date only.

Controls the maximum number of values in the ·value space· of datatypes ·derived· from decimal, by restricting it to numbers that are expressible as i × 10^-n where i and n are integers such that |i| < 10^totalDigits and 0 <= n <= totalDigits. Numeric only.

Controls the size of the minimum difference between values in the ·value space· of datatypes ·derived· from decimal, by restricting the ·value space· to numbers that are expressible as i × 10^-n where i and n are integers and 0 <= n <= fractionDigits. Numeric only.
